If the graph intersects itself, then there exist two values of $t$ such that $(\cos t + \frac{t}{2}, \sin t) = (\cos u + \frac{u}{2}, \sin u)$ for $t \neq u.$  This means
\begin{align*}
\cos t + \frac{t}{2} &= \cos u + \frac{u}{2}, \\
\sin t &= \sin u.
\end{align*}From the second equation, $u = t + 2k \pi$ or $u = \pi - t + 2k \pi$ for some integer $k.$

If $u = t + 2k \pi,$ then
\[\cos t + \frac{t}{2} = \cos (t + 2k \pi) + \frac{t + 2k \pi}{2}.\]Then $\cos t - \cos (t + 2k \pi) = -k \pi,$ so $2 \sin \frac{t + 2k \pi}{2} \sin \frac{t}{2} = -k \pi.$  Since the $\sin$ terms have absolute value at most 1, $k = 0.$  Hence, $u = t,$ which contradicts $t \neq u.$

