Then by the angle bisector theorem, $\frac{BP}{PE} = \frac{BD}{DE}.$  By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\cos A = \frac{7^2 + 5^2 - 3^2}{2 \cdot 7 \cdot 5} = \frac{13}{35}.\]Also, $\angle BPD = \frac{A}{2}$ and $\angle EPD = \frac{180^\circ - A}{2},$ so by the Law of Cosines on triangles $BPD$ and $EPD,$
\begin{align*}
BD^2 &= BP^2 + \left( \frac{7}{12} BC \right)^2 - 2 BP \cdot \frac{7}{12} BC \cos \frac{A}{2}, \\
DE^2 &= EP^2 + \left( \frac{5}{12} BC \right)^2 - 2 EP \cdot \frac{5}{12} BC \cos \frac{180^\circ - A}{2}.
\end{align*}Hence,
\begin{align*}
\frac{BD}{DE} &= \sqrt{\frac{BP^2 + \frac{49}{144} BC^2 - \frac{7}{6} BP \cdot BC \cos \frac{A}{2}}{EP^2 + \frac{25}{144} BC^2 + \frac{5}{6} EP \cdot BC \cos \frac{A}{2}}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{BP^2 + \frac{49}{144} BC^2 - \frac{7}{6} BP \cdot BC \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos A}{2}}}{EP^2 + \frac{25}{144} BC^2 + \frac{5}{6} EP \cdot BC \sqrt{\frac{1 - \cos A}{2}}}}.
\end{align*}From $\cos A = \frac{13}{35},$ we get $\sin^2 \frac{A}{2} = \frac{11}{35}$ and $\cos^2 \frac{A}{2} = \frac{24}{35},$ so
\begin{align*}
\frac{BD}{DE} &= \sqrt{\frac{BP^2 + \frac{49}{144} BC^2 - \frac{7}{6} BP \cdot BC \cdot \frac{3 \sqrt{11}}{10}}{EP^2 + \frac{25}{144} BC^2 + \frac{5}{6} EP \cdot BC \cdot \frac{\sqrt{14}}{2}}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{BP^2 + \frac{49}{144} BC^2 - \frac{21 \sqrt{11}}{120} BP \cdot BC}{EP^2 + \frac{25}{144} BC^2 + \frac{5 \sqrt{14}}{12} EP \cdot BC}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{BP^2 + \frac{49}{144} \cdot 3^2 - \frac{21 \sqrt{11}}{120} BP \cdot 3}{EP^2 + \frac{25}{144} \cdot 3^2 + \frac{5 \sqrt{14}}{12} EP \cdot 3}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{BP^2 + \frac{49}{16} - \frac{7 \sqrt{11}}{40} BP}{EP^2 + \frac{25}{16} + \frac{5 \sqrt{14}}{4} EP}}.
\end{align*}Note that $BP + EP = \frac{7}{12} \cdot 3 = \frac{7}{4},$ so
\[\frac{BP}{EP} = \frac{7}{4} - EP,\]and
\[\frac{BP^2}{EP^2} = \frac{49}{16} - \frac{7}{2} EP + EP^2.\]Hence,
\[\frac{BD}{DE} = \sqrt{\frac{\frac{49}{16} - \frac{7 \sqrt{11}}{40} BP}{\frac{25}{16} + \frac{5 \sqrt{14}}{4} EP + \frac{49}{16} - \frac{7}{2} EP + EP^2}} = \sqrt{\frac{\frac{49}{16} - \frac{7 \sqrt{11}}{40} BP}{EP^2 - \frac{7}{2} EP + \frac{74}{16}}}\]and
\[\frac{BP^2}{EP^2} = \frac{49}{16} - \frac{7}{2} EP + EP^2.\]Thus,
\[\frac{BP}{EP} = \sqrt{\frac{\frac{49}{16} - \frac{7 \sqrt{11}}{40} BP}{\frac{49}{16} - \frac{7}{2} EP + EP^2}}.\]Let $x = \frac{BP}{EP}.$  Then
\[\frac{49}{16} - \frac{7 \sqrt{11}}{40} BP = \frac{49}{16} x^2 - \frac{7}{2} EP x + EP^2.\]Also,
\[BP^2 + EP^2 = \left( \frac{7}{4} - EP \right)^2,\]so
\[\frac{49}{16} x^2 - \frac{7}{2} EP x + EP^2 + \frac{49}{16} - \frac{7 \sqrt{11}}{40} BP = \frac{49}{16} - \frac{49}{8} EP + \frac{49}{16} - \frac{7}{2} \sqrt{11} \cdot \frac{BP}{EP} + \left( \frac{7}{4} - EP \right)^2.\]Hence,
\[\frac{49}{16} x^2 - \frac{7}{2} EP x + EP^2 - \frac{49}{8} EP + \frac{7}{2} \sqrt{11} \cdot \frac{BP}{EP} + \frac{7}{4} - \frac{7}{2} \sqrt{11} \cdot \frac{BP}{EP} + \frac{25}{16} - \frac{7}{2} EP = 0.\]This simplifies to
\[\frac{49}{16} x^2 - 7x + \frac{25}{16} = 0.\]This factors as $\left( x - \frac{5}{7} \right) \left( \frac{49}{16} x - 5 \right) = 0,$ so $x = \frac{5}{7}$ or $x = \frac{5}{16}.$  Since $x$ is clearly positive, $x = \boxed{\frac{5}{7}}.$

